Case study: How does a bike-share navigate speedy success?

Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working on the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes dirently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

Characters and teams

  • Cyclistic: A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who cant use a standard two-wheeled bike. The majority of riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use the bikes to commute to work each day.
  • Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.
  • Cyclistic marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts who are responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Cyclistic marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Cyclistics mission and business goalsas well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Cyclistic achieve them.
  • Cyclistic executive team: The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the recommended marketing program.

About the Company

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime.

Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members. Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a solid opportunity to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Ask

Moreno has assigned you the the following question to answer: How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

You will produce a report with the following deliverables:

  1. A clear statement of the business task
  2. A description of all data sources used
  3. Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data
  4. A summary of your analysis
  5. Supporting visualizations and key findings
  6. Your top three recommendations based on your analysis

Prepare

Because Cyclistic is a fictional company there is no real-world data however there is data from Divvy Bikes made available by Motivate International Inc.under this licensce. This dataset has the ride information going back to 2013, however it was split by quarter till 2020 after which it was split my month. In order to ensure that data is consitent I would like to combine the last 12 months, June 2023 - May 2024 into one large data set to analyze.

This is first party data collected directly from the company saved in a CSV format. In order to conduct an analysis in R we need to import the CSV files into one dataframe. Doing so will allow for us to use R libraries in order to clean, analyze and plot the data.

Process

We have data from the last 12 months of Cyclistic trip data. First we need to load the data and to make this cleaner I want to load all 12 months of data into one data frame.

Now I want to split the date time for started_at and ended_at into start date, end date, and start time, end time columns. I also want to add a column for the month.

ride_data$start_date <- as.Date(ride_data$started_at)
ride_data$start_time <- format(as.POSIXct(ride_data$started_at),
                         format = "%H:%M:%S")
ride_data$end_date <- as.Date(ride_data$ended_at)
ride_data$end_time <- format(as.POSIXct(ride_data$ended_at),
                         format = "%H:%M:%S")

ride_data$month <- format(as.Date(ride_data$start_date, format="%d/%m/%Y"),"%m")
ride_data$weekday <- weekdays(ride_data$start_date, abbreviate = TRUE)

head(ride_data)

It looks like the start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id dont have much data, but we have the start_lat, start_lng and the end_lat, end_lng. Let us look into the station names and ids further to see if we can omit this information.

ride_data %>% 
  drop_na(c("start_station_name", "start_station_id", "end_station_name", "end_station_id"))

We can see that we lost about 1.5 million rows of data, however there are ~4.3 million rows of data that has the information we need. In this case I will omit the 1.5 million rides without a start and end station since our goal is to determine the riding habits between members and casual riders and we can get trends based on the data we have left.

ride_data <- ride_data %>% 
  drop_na(c("start_station_name", "start_station_id", "end_station_name", "end_station_id"))

Alternatively if we had a data set with station_name, station_id, station_lng, station_lat then we could fill in missing information based on the latitude and longitude.

Now let us look at the specific min, max, and mean of ride_time and the mode of weekday for both members and casual riders.

find_mode <- function(x) {
  u <- unique(x)
  tab <- tabulate(match(x, u))
  u[tab == max(tab)]
}
min(member_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 1
max(member_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 89859
mean(member_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 745.7826
find_mode(member_data$weekday)
[1] "Thu"
min(casual_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 1
max(casual_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 669136
mean(casual_data$ride_time, na.rm = FALSE)
[1] 1415.332
find_mode(casual_data$weekday)
[1] "Sat"

We can see that casual riders have longer rides on average and this lines up with the fact that most of their rides happen on Saturdays. Members will use bikes more frequently, but for less time since they are most likely using them to get somewhere fast where as casual riders are more likely to take bikes to see the city and ride around leisurely. I predict that casual riders will ride more in the summer months vs members, but let us get a count.


ggplot(
  data = ride_data,
  mapping = aes(x = month, fill = member_casual)
) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")


ggplot(
  data = ride_data,
  mapping = aes(x = weekday, fill = member_casual)
) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")

We can see that for both members and casual riders there are more rides registered during warmer months, June - September. However, during colder months while there are less riders, members still utilize Cyclistic services proportionally more than casual riders. This makes sense if members use Cyclistic to commute to work. We can also see that members use Cyclistic the most on Thursdays while casual riders use Cyclistic the most on Saturdays which we saw when looking at the mode earlier. However we get additional information from the above graph which shows us that members have the most usage on Wednesday - Thursday, with the lowest usage being on the weekend, the opposite of casual riders.

Now let us look at the average ride time.

avg_time_weekday <- aggregate( ride_time ~ weekday + member_casual, ride_data , mean )

avg_time_weekday

ggplot(
  data = avg_time_weekday,
  mapping = aes(x = weekday, y = ride_time, fill = member_casual)
) + geom_bar(stat='identity', position = "dodge")

avg_time_month <- aggregate( ride_time ~ month + member_casual, ride_data , mean )

avg_time_month

ggplot(
  data = avg_time_month,
  mapping = aes(x = month, y = ride_time, fill = member_casual)
) + geom_bar(stat='identity', position = "dodge")
